<TITLE> European stocks snap winning run as banks fall </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, Dec 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European stocks dipped in early trade on Friday, falling for the first time in five sessions as banking shares slipped on renewed worries over the global credit crisis. Geopolitical concerns following the assassination of Pakistani opposition leader Benazir Bhutto also dampened the mood on equity markets across the world. At 0808 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was down 0.3 percent at 1,504.99 points. Europe's benchmark index is up 1.4 percent on the year, on track to record its worst annual performance since 2002. HSBC was down 0.7 percent, HBOS down 1.8 percent and Credit Suisse down 0.9 percent. A Goldman Sachs analyst said on Thursday Citigroup Inc, Merrill Lynch & Co and JPMorgan Chase & Co may face larger fourth-quarter debt write-offs than previously expected, while Citigroup may also need to cut its dividend. The Wall Street Journal reported on its Web site on Friday that US and European banks including Citigroup and HSBC are considering sales of part of their businesses from branches to entire units in a nod to more testing times ahead. "This report is not good news at all," one trader said. "With no corporate updates scheduled for the next three weeks, the market will get its direction from (such) surprise bad news." Banking shares have been hit over the past few months by a squeeze in the credit market, and investors fear that financial institutions have not yet unveiled the full impact of the debacle in the US subprime mortgage market on their books. Weak durable goods data released on Thursday also fuelled worries over the outlook for the US econo
